Predicting medical costs

Let's use medical cost data set with demographic information and individual characteristics and contruct the best possible predictive model for the medical cost using linear regression.

Puneet Pawar Wed 07 January 2026 Wed 07 January 2026
machine_learning sklearn regression feature_engineering polynomial

Predicting Medical Costs¶

For this project, we will be looking at the Medical Cost Data Set. This dataset contains information on individual medical insurance bills. Each bill is associated with some demographic and personal characteristics of the person who received it.

We are interested in how these different characteristics relate to the total medical cost. It's a continuous, positive number, which makes it a good candidate for a linear regression. For this guided project, we want to construct the best possible predictive model for the cost, given some information about the patient. Predicting medical costs is an important task because it allows hospitals to predict revenue and plan necessary procedures needed by its patient population.

Data dictionary:

Column Description
age age of primary beneficiary
sex gender of primary beneficiary, female, male
bmi Body mass index (kg / m ^ 2), ideally 18.5 to 24.9
children Number of children covered by health insurance / Number of dependents
smoker whether the beneficiary is a smoker (yes/no)
region the beneficiary's residential area in the US, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest.
charges Individual medical costs

EDA observations:

  1. There are no missing values. Dataset has 1338 observations with 6 features and 1 target column- 'charges'. 3 of these features are categorical : sex, smoker and region.
  2. 'age' has roughly uniform distribution, 'bmi' has normal distribution while distribution of 'children' is right skewed.
  3. Target column 'charges' is heavily right skewed with extreme outliers.
  4. 'charges' has significant correltion with 'age', 'bmi' and 'smoker'. These will be good predictors. All of these are also relevant health indicators.
  5. Dataset has roughly balanced proportion of all classes in 'sex' and 'region', while for 'smoker' we have 80% non-smokers and only 20% smokers. We will stratify the split by 'smoker' to ensure both categories have same proportion in train and test set.
  6. numeric features are not showing significant multicollinearity.

Residuals are not homoscedastic, variance is not constant. This is violating the assumptions of linear model. Extreme outliers we have in the target can be on of the reasons. Also 'bmi' doesn't seem to have a linear relationship with the target.

We have following coefficient for 'age', 'bmi' and 'smoker': [3660.68578407, 1835.87425158, 9595.57966687] This means:

  • average increase in 'charges' for a unit increase in 'age', holding the other predictors constant = 3660.68
  • average increase in 'charges' for a unit increase in 'bmi', holding the other predictors constant = 1835.87
  • average increase in 'charges' for a smoker compared to non-smoker, holding the other predictors constant = 9595.57

This tells us that the most important feature for this model in terms of predictions is 'smoker' since it has a biggest coefficient. This doesn't imply causality.

Model Improvements¶

We can clearly see that residuals are not homoscedastic. So let's explore a couple of things to see how we can improve the linear model.

  1. Smoker vs non-smoker analysis. We might find out that the data has different patterns for the two categories.
  2. Implementing interaction terms like age * is_smoker and bmi * is_smoker etc.

Distribution is not very different based on 'region' and 'sex'. But smoker and non-smoker has different distributions. So building a separate model for smokers and non-smokers might be a good idea as medical cost pattern differs significantly. But we only have 20% smokers in the dataset of 1338 observations, so building separate models may require more data for smokers.

Conclusion¶

  • We identified the features which are best predictors for the medical cost - age, bmi and whether the individual is a smoker.
  • We also found out that medical cost patterns are significantly different between smokers' and non-smokers.
  • We used interaction features like age * is_smoker and bmi * is_smoker and polynomial features to improve the predictability of the model.
  • Target is extremely right skewed and the model can benefit further from log transformation or something similar.
  • The residuals are not homoscedastic with the current model and that violates the linear model assumptions. That means the model cannot be used for inferential analysis but might still do a decent job as a predictor.
  • And we have r-squared of 0.85 and mse of 2.12e+07 on test set but it can definitely be improved further.
